{
  "id": "jshell-301",
  "name": "JShell 301 — Streams & Functional Programming",
  "description": "Learn Java Streams: a declarative way to process collections using filter, map, reduce, collect, and more. Includes a practical employee data pipeline.",
  "created": "2026-03-29T00:00:00",
  "modified": "2026-03-29T00:00:00",
  "cells": [
    {
      "id": "jshell-301-intro",
      "type": "MARKDOWN",
      "mode": "jshell",
      "source": "# JShell 301 — Streams & Functional Programming\n\n**Streams** (introduced in Java 8) let you process sequences of elements in a **declarative, pipeline style** — you describe *what* you want, not *how* to do it.\n\n```\ndata source → [intermediate ops] → terminal op\nList       → filter → map → sorted → collect\n```\n\n**Key rules:**\n1. A Stream is **lazy** — intermediate operations do nothing until a terminal operation is called.\n2. A Stream can only be **consumed once** — create a new one each time.\n3. Streams don't modify the original collection.\n\n## What you'll learn\n- Creating streams (`stream()`, `Stream.of()`, `Arrays.stream()`)\n- Intermediate ops: `filter`, `map`, `sorted`, `distinct`, `limit`, `flatMap`\n- Terminal ops: `collect`, `reduce`, `forEach`, `count`, `min`, `max`, `findFirst`\n- `Collectors.groupingBy` and `Collectors.toMap`\n- `Optional` — Java's null-safe wrapper",
      "output": "",
      "returnValue": null,
      "executed": false,
      "executionCount": null,
